the structural lipids of brain cell mem-
branes, including those of the synaptic
terminals,17-21
and children with
ADHD have been shown to have low
plasma and erythrocyte phospholipid
levels of DHA.22,23 Assuming that
brain levels also are low, it has been
argued that DHA supplementation
will increase levels and that the result-
ing alterations in synaptic transmis-
sion will decrease the symptoms of
ADHD. Indeed, despite a lack of data
to support either efficacy or safety,
DHA supplements are readily avail-
able and are being marketed for the
treatment of children with ADHD.16
The objective of this study was to de-
termine the efficacy of DHA supple-
mentation in reducing symptoms of
ADHD.

